cale events. Tragedy Plus Time is the first comprehensive work to investigate tragedy-driven comedy in the aftermaths of such traumas as the JFK assassination and 9/11, as well as during the administration of Donald Trump. Focusing on the mass publicization of television comedy, Scepanski considers issues of censorship and memory construction in the ways comedians negotiate emotions, politics, war, race, and Islamophobia. Amid the media frenzy and conflicting expressions of grief following a public tragedy, comedians provoke or risk controversy to grapple publicly with national traumas that all Americans are trying to understand for themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aAmerican wit and humorxSocial aspects. 0aAmericansxPsychology. 0aDisastersxHumorxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aDisasters--Humor--Social aspects--United States. 0aPsychic traumaxHumorxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPsychic trauma--Humor--Social aspects--United States. 0aTelevision comediesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTelevision comedies--Social aspects--United States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074527640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32254340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477322550423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477322550/original  a978-3-11-074527-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK